<subSubSection lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="32" pageId="17" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[801,1453,1591,1903]" pageId="17" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis box="[839,899,1592,1615]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="30">Notes</emphasis>
. – The flower of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gardere. A. Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[1114,1262,1591,1615]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Campanulaceae" genus="Campanula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="17" pageNumber="30" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vicinituba">
<emphasis box="[1114,1262,1591,1615]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="30">C. vicinituba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very close to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gardere. Dumicolous" authorityYear="2021" box="[801,934,1623,1647]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Campanulaceae" genus="Campanula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="17" pageNumber="30" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fransinea">
<emphasis box="[801,934,1623,1647]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="30">C. fransinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the corolla shapes of both species are infundibuliform but for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gardere. A. Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[1019,1161,1655,1679]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Campanulaceae" genus="Campanula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="17" pageNumber="30" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vicinituba">
<emphasis box="[1019,1161,1655,1679]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="30">C. vicinituba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the corolla appears to be slightly more flared and shorter than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gardere. Dumicolous" authorityYear="2021" box="[1209,1336,1687,1711]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Campanulaceae" genus="Campanula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="17" pageNumber="30" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fransinea">
<emphasis box="[1209,1336,1687,1711]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="30">C. fransinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gardere. A. Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[801,940,1719,1743]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Campanulaceae" genus="Campanula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="17" pageNumber="30" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vicinituba">
<emphasis box="[801,940,1719,1743]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="30">C. vicinituba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be identified easily by the indument of its primary and secondary venation and those of its margins of calyx-lobes which consist of bulbous and appressed trichomes. Furthermore, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gardere. A. Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[946,1077,1815,1839]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Campanulaceae" genus="Campanula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="17" pageNumber="30" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vicinituba">
<emphasis box="[946,1077,1815,1839]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="30">C. vicinituba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
presents a tortuous habit and leaves adaxially glabrescent and glossy, characters unique among CVB species; its flowers are always purple-blue.
</paragraph>
